Creating a Discord bot using the TypeScript language and Eris library to filter out online users with the "Europe" role set involves several steps. This guide assumes you have basic knowledge of TypeScript and Eris, and have Node.js and npm installed.

1. Setting up your project:
Create a new directory, open a terminal in that directory, and run the following commands:

```sh
npm init -y
npm install --save eris
npm install --save-dev typescript ts-node @types/node
```

2. Add a "tsconfig.json" file in your project directory with the following content:

```json
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "target": "ES2017",
    "module": "commonjs",
    "strict": true,
    "esModuleInterop": true
  },
  "include": ["src"]
}
```

3. Create a "src" directory and inside it create a "index.ts" file for your bot.

4. Add a simple bot code to your "index.ts":

```ts
import { Client, Member } from 'eris';

// Read your bot token from the environment variables.
const token = process.env.BOT_TOKEN;

// Initialize the Eris client.
const bot = new Client(token);

// Listen to the "ready" event.
bot.on('ready', () => {
  console.log('Bot is ready!');
  filterOnlineEuropeRoleMembers();
});

// Define the filter function.
async function filterOnlineEuropeRoleMembers() {
  const guild = bot.guilds.get('your-guild-id');
  const role = guild.roles.find((r) => r.name === 'Europe');

  const onlineEuropeMembers = guild.members.filter(
    (member: Member) =>
      member.roles.includes(role.id) && member.status === 'online',
  );

  // Log the user count and usernames.
  console.log('Online users with Europe role:', onlineEuropeMembers.length);
  onlineEuropeMembers.map((member: Member) =>
    console.log(`- ${member.username}`),
  );
}

// Connect the bot to Discord.
bot.connect();
```

Don't forget to replace `'your-guild-id'` with the actual ID of your guild.

5. Set up start and build commands in your "package.json". Add the following in the "scripts" section:

```json
"scripts": {
  "build": "tsc",
  "start": "ts-node src/index.ts"
}
```

6. To run your Discord bot, ensure you have created your Discord bot and added it to your server, then set your bot token as an environment variable while running it:

```sh
BOT_TOKEN=<your-bot-token> npm start
```

Now, your bot should be running and it should filter and log online users with the "Europe" role.

